.TH CMXD 8 "November 2025" "cmxd 5.0.2" "System Management Commands"
.SH NAME
cmxd \- Chuwi Minibook X tablet mode daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B cmxd
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B cmxd
is a userspace daemon that detects tablet mode for the Chuwi Minibook X convertible laptop. It reads accelerometer data from IIO devices, calculates hinge angles and device orientation, and communicates with the
.B cmx
kernel module to generate tablet mode input events.

The daemon operates in an event-driven manner using IIO triggers, minimizing CPU usage while providing responsive mode detection.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-timeout\-ms " \fIMS\fR"
Buffer read timeout in milliseconds. This is the timeout for the poll() system call waiting for IIO buffer data, not a polling interval. Default: 100. Valid range: 1-10000.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-sysfs\-path " \fIPATH\fR"
Path to the kernel module's sysfs directory. Default: /sys/devices/platform/cmx. Override only if using a custom kernel module path.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Enable verbose logging. Shows all debug information including accelerometer readings, angle calculations, and mode transitions.
.TP
.BR \-\-no\-dbus
Disable DBus event publishing. By default, the daemon publishes orientation and mode changes via DBus for desktop integration (iio-sensor-proxy compatibility).
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display usage information and exit.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Display version information and exit.

.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is read from
.I /etc/default/cmxd
if present. The file supports the following variables:

.TP
.B BUFFER_TIMEOUT_MS
Buffer read timeout in milliseconds (same as \fB\-t\fR option).
.TP
.B SYSFS_DIR
Kernel module sysfs path (same as \fB\-s\fR option).

Command line options override configuration file settings.

.SH DEVICE DETECTION
Device assignments are automatically detected from the
.B cmx
kernel module. The daemon reads the
.I iio_base_device
and
.I iio_lid_device
attributes from the kernel module's sysfs interface to determine which IIO devices correspond to base and lid accelerometers.

.SH MODES
The daemon detects four device modes based on hinge angle:
.TP
.B laptop
Traditional laptop position (45° - 160°)
.TP
.B flat
Device lying flat or opening towards flat (160° - 240°)
.TP
.B tent
Tent mode - lid folded back (240° - 345°)
.TP
.B tablet
Fully folded back for tablet use (345° - 360°)

A dead zone (0° - 45°) maintains the current mode to prevent jitter during device manipulation.

.SH ORIENTATIONS
The daemon detects four screen orientations matching iio-sensor-proxy naming:
.TP
.B normal
Standard landscape orientation
.TP
.B right-up
Device rotated 90° clockwise (portrait)
.TP
.B left-up
Device rotated 90° counter-clockwise (portrait flipped)
.TP
.B bottom-up
Device rotated 180° (landscape flipped)

.SH COMMUNICATION
The daemon communicates through multiple channels:
.TP
.B Sysfs
Writes accelerometer data, mode, and orientation to the kernel module via
.IR /sys/devices/platform/cmx/ .
.TP
.B Unix Socket
Publishes JSON events to
.I /run/cmxd/events.sock
for client applications.
.TP
.B DBus
Emits iio-sensor-proxy compatible signals on the system bus (unless disabled with \fB\-\-no-dbus\fR).

.SH SIGNALS
.TP
.B SIGTERM, SIGINT
Gracefully shutdown the daemon, cleaning up resources and resetting the kernel module state.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/default/cmxd
Configuration file
.TP
.I /sys/devices/platform/cmx/
Kernel module sysfs interface
.TP
.I /run/cmxd/events.sock
Unix domain socket for event publication
.TP
.I /var/log/syslog
Log messages (when running as service)

.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.B cmx kernel module
Platform driver that creates sysfs interface and generates input events
.TP
.B IIO accelerometers
Two MXC4005 accelerometer devices (base and lid)
.TP
.B DBus (optional)
System bus for desktop integration

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Run with defaults (auto-detected devices):
.B cmxd

.TP
Verbose mode for debugging:
.B cmxd -v

.TP
Custom buffer timeout:
.B cmxd -t 50

.TP
Disable DBus integration:
.B cmxd --no-dbus

.TP
Custom sysfs path:
.B cmxd -s /sys/devices/platform/custom-cmx

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
General error (missing devices, initialization failure, etc.)

.SH NOTES
The daemon automatically configures accelerometers to their least sensitive scale setting for stable mode detection. This reduces noise and prevents false mode transitions.

The daemon requires root privileges to access IIO devices and communicate with the kernel module.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cmx (4),
.BR cmxsd (8),
.BR iio_event_monitor (1),
.BR evtest (1)

